How to finance the green transition
New York — This week, world leaders gathered in New York at the United Nations to assess the global fight against climate change and present new commitments to reduce emissions.
The climate crisis is a matter of great importance, and our pace of action is far too slow.
We have been unable to enter the fast lane for a long time.
Accelerating the pace of change requires the collaborative efforts of both public and private stakeholders.
Fortunately, through the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), private sector collaboration to combat climate change is increasing.
The CFLI was established under the leadership of Michael Bloomberg, the UN Special Envoy for Climate Action, with the aim of mobilizing global private capital to address this critical issue.
This month, CFLI released a new report titled "Financing the Low Carbon Future," outlining how to expand green finance to support a orderly transition to a low-carbon economy, and identifying public-private partnership opportunities to achieve the goals of the 2015 Paris Climate Agreement.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects worldwide.
But now, in response to the call from European heads of state and the newly elected President of the European Commission, Ursula von der Leyen, we are ready to take on a greater ambition and strengthen the EIB's role as the EU's dedicated climate bank.
The EIB will mainstream climate considerations, focus on targeted low-carbon investments, and commit at least 1 trillion euros over the next decade to low-carbon projects.
To achieve this goal, by 2025, at least 50% of EIB financing will be allocated to climate action and environmental sustainability.
By the end of 2020, we will have reorganized all our financing activities to align with the objectives of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will exclude energy projects that rely on fossil fuels.
In addition, we will position the EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing other resources to help various economies transition toward a low-carbon future.
As an EU bank, our mission is to invest in Europe's future, and among the most important issues is climate change.
The more urgent the climate crisis, the stronger our determination.
This summer, European countries experienced record-breaking heat and poor crop yields, due to the drought last year.
Many developing countries also have similar experiences.
Floods and other climate-related phenomena cost major cities billions of dollars each year and threaten the lives of many more people.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity, as funding new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution that plagues major cities around the world.
Shifting investment patterns can accelerate the transition away from fossil fuels. This transition has already begun.
Market forces are increasingly favoring clean energy and moving away from fossil fuels.
In 2011, half of the coal-fired power plants in the United States retired, while the clean energy industry created 3.3 million jobs, compared to less than 100,000 jobs in the coal industry.
In addition, an increasing number of American cities and states have pledged to achieve net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will receive support from the Beyond Carbon initiative, launched last year by the Bloomberg Philanthropies Foundation, aimed at supporting the full decarbonization of the U.S. economy.
As an international community, we must not only invest in clean energy but also reduce our investments in dirty energy.
Currently, in terms of fossil fuel subsidies, we are essentially spending money to promote climate change and air pollution.
These public funds should be used to guide investments toward electric vehicles and other technologies that can drive the transformation of the energy landscape.
These investments will yield substantial returns, including reducing the significant costs to public health caused by air pollution.
In addition, we can take various measures to guide the necessary funds.
First, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For a long time, enterprises and investors were unaware of climate-related risks, not knowing the rationale for reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from the impacts of extreme weather.
This is beginning to change.
The recommendations of the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding companies to allocate capital in more sustainable ways and enabling investors to reward those companies that seriously address climate change.
Secondly, we must clarify the investment risks related to green finance.
Cities account for more than 70% of carbon dioxide emissions, but only a few cities in the developing world are able to obtain credit ratings.
As a result, the total investment in clean public transport, energy-efficient buildings, and other emission-reduction projects was affected.
Governments and listed banks must increase their efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including initiatives such as the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the European Investment Bank (EIB) and jointly led by the Bloomberg Philanthropies foundation.
Third, we need to modernize the power grid.
Incentives such as refunds and tax benefits have promoted the expansion of wind and solar power, reducing costs for businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar plans to accelerate the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies, thereby speeding up the resolution of intermittency issues.
Furthermore, better grid connectivity can enable regions with surplus wind and solar power to supply electricity to regions experiencing shortages.
The government can play a leading role in these two areas, encouraging more private investment to flow into clean energy.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, the EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, and since then, the green bond market has expanded to $136 billion.
But compared to the global bond market of $100 trillion, this is just a drop in the bucket.
Therefore, the EIB is helping the EU develop a classification for sustainable finance standards, so that investors can compare similar projects, just like standard bonds.
More and better information on carbon footprints can enable investors to make informed decisions, thereby driving more private investment into low-carbon projects.
This is how we provide financing for the green transition.
